rtifact carries all RabbitMQ AMQP 1.0 client and Spring dependencies. I'm aware of potential risks with Docker image vulnerabilities and whether a test setup identifies the image correctly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"The artifact is a Spring adapter for RabbitMQ's AMQP 1.0 Java client. Its resolved dependencies already include the required Spring AMQP and RabbitMQ client artifacts, but meaningful end-to-end coverage normally needs a RabbitMQ broker; upstream Spring AMQP tests use a RabbitMQ Testcontainers broker.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"docker_image\",\n      \"image\": \"rabbitmq:4.1-management\",\n      \"slug\": \"rabbitmq\",\n      \"reason\": \"RabbitMQ AMQP Java Client 1.1.0 requires RabbitMQ 4.0+, and Spring's own spring-rabbitmq-client integration tests run against a RabbitMQ broker with the management image.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"If adding broker-backed coverage, start the broker before tests, wait until an AMQP connection can be opened on port 5672, create an Environment/SingleAmqpConnectionFactory, and exercise RabbitAmqpAdmin plus RabbitAmqpTemplate publish/receive/listener paths against declared test queues/exchanges. Cleanly close Spring AMQP resources and the client Environment.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Existing repository tests use fake RabbitMQ AMQP client objects; keeping that style may be sufficient for the javac API-fix scope and avoids Docker flakiness.\",\n    \"A live broker test broadens coverage but can make native-image verification slower and more sensitive to container startup timing.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0fdbf1f33ae51eb0016a2872fffa8c81939de19bc02f757d24\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1573, "output": 1356, "cacheRead": 50688, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 53617, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0,